Author:
Vol / Page: 2
Edition:
Quote: Two parties, however, were nearly or altogether impracticable [sic], - the extreme Churchmen and the extreme Dissenters. The former claimed it as the chartered and sacred right of the Established Clergy to be the sole educators of the people (so far at least as religious instruction was concerned), and the latter carried their Voluntaryism to the length of a total rejection of State aid for Schools, - unless indeed, it could be obtained on the obviously impossible condition of exemption from Governmental inspection.
